  "method": [
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Devein whole prawns first by piercing the back of the body with a knife and poking in to release and discard the intestinal tract. Then remove just the body shell, leaving the heads on."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Pat dry the prawns very well on kitchen paper, as they need to be dry to cook in the pan. Set aside in the fridge."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Meanwhile, make the seafood sauce. Into a blender add all the ingredients and pulse until you have a green dressing. Do not over blend this, as you want fine even chunks. Pour into a serving bowl and skim off any foam."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Finely slice the garlic cloves for the prawns, if you have a mandoline this will speed up the process."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Now, cook the prawns. Pour a splash of olive oil into a large frying pan set over a high heat, with a pinch of salt into the oil, then add the prawns and cook for 2 min on each side, allowing the prawns to sear without any interference. Now remove the charred prawns onto a plate (they will get cooked again). Now add all the garlic and a glug of olive oil and tilt the pan, allowing all the garlic to sizzle in the pool of oil for 2 mins or until lightly golden, then return the prawns with a Tbsp of oyster sauce and toss everything together. Turn the heat off and serve into a large plate with all the juices and garlic pieces."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Garnish the prawns with some coriander leaves, cucumbers and the nam jim seafood dipping sauce."
    }
  ],
